Augmentation of a global navigation satellite system (GNSS)
Furkan Danishman, Nga Nguyen
Faculty of Science, York University
Introduction/Objective
In dense urban environments, ulizing Global Navigaon Satellite System (GNSS)
for localizaon presents numerous challenges due to:
Signal obstrucons caused by tall buildings and vehicles.
Mulpath interference from surrounding structures.
This study addresses these challenges, parcularly in context of data collected
from smartphones equipped with GNSS receivers.
Invesgang outlier detecon methods to enhance reliability of GNSS data
in urban sengs.
Highlighng dierences between each technique to give insight about
advantages and disadvantages.
Methodology
Our data consists of 132 satellites and 1631 epochs, collected by driving a vehicle
equipped with Xiaomi and Samsung smartphones around urban areas.
Outlier detecon methods were implemented to idenfy and migate localizaon
errors caused by non-line-of-sight and mulpath anomalies. The methodology of
this study goes beyond the limitaons of prior studies and has never been imple-
mented in context of GNSS before.

Analysis
T-test, LOF, and IF-LOF methods used predetermined threshold values of 90%-
97% condence levels. Observaons under 90-97 region were transformed by a
3-segment adapve factor technique, and beyond 97 was considered an outlier.

Conclusion
In the study, we invesgated outlier detecon techniques to enhance the reliability
of GNSS data in dense urban environments.
IF-LOF test performed the worst results due to small data set of epochs
While isolaon forest (IF) performed relavely well, it removed signicantly
more observaons, which resulted in deducon of degrees of freedom
The main dierence between t-test and LOF is caused due to data behavior.
For the local tests, LOF has the most successful results, especially under large
quanle values. However, it removes a small set of reliable GPS satellites
In conclusion, t-test and LOF have the most opmized results, LOF being slightly
more robust. Thus, t-test or LOF methods can be implemented depending on our
condence about the assumpon of data behaviour. Under uncertainty, with this
newly introduced methodology in GNSS context, LOF would be the best opon.
These ndings can signicantly improve GNSS datas reliability in dense urban en-
vironments. Its a step forward in enhancements to the posioning algorithm.
